There are two approaches:

The first one is to use an existing crate, like [walkdir][1]. The benefit is it&#39;s being well tested and offers many options.

The second one is to write your own implementation of Iterator. Here&#39;s an example, and maybe the basis for your own:

```rust
struct FileIterator {
    dirs: Vec&lt;PathBuf&gt;, // the dirs waiting to be read
    files: Option&lt;ReadDir&gt;, // non recursive iterator over the currently read dir
}

impl From&lt;&amp;str&gt; for FileIterator {
    fn from(path: &amp;str) -&gt; Self {
        FileIterator {
            dirs: vec![PathBuf::from(path)],
            files: None,
        }
    }
}

impl Iterator for FileIterator {
    type Item = PathBuf;
    fn next(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Option&lt;PathBuf&gt; {
        loop {
            while let Some(read_dir) = &amp;mut self.files {
                match read_dir.next() {
                    Some(Ok(entry)) =&gt; {
                        let path = entry.path();
                        if let Ok(md) = entry.metadata() {
                            if md.is_dir() {
                                self.dirs.push(path.clone());
                                continue;
                            }
                        }
                        return Some(path);
                    }
                    None =&gt; { // we consumed this directory
                        self.files = None;
                        break; 
                    }
                    _ =&gt; { }
                }
            }
            while let Some(dir) = self.dirs.pop() {
                let read_dir = fs::read_dir(&amp;dir);
                if let Ok(files) = read_dir {
                    self.files = Some(files);
                    return Some(dir);
                }
            }
            break; // no more files, no more dirs
        }
        return None;
    }
}
```

[playground][2]

The advantage of writing your own iterator is that you&#39;ll tune it for your precise needs (sorting, filtering, error handling, etc.). But you&#39;ll have to deal with your own bugs.


  [1]: https://docs.rs/walkdir/2.2.9/walkdir/
  [2]: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2018&amp;gist=d0a2b5f077fc85cfc5d273a621ab960b

This is the exact solution I sought. It&#39;s none of my achievement; see [here](https://users.rust-lang.org/t/flat-map-and-chaining-iterators/32938). Comments are welcome.

